               <p>WARWICK HELE TONKIN, THE YOUNGER. On the 28th of September, I was in <placeName id="t18251027-49-crimeloc273">Oxford-road, near the top of Regent-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18251027-49-crimeloc273" type="placeName" value="Oxford-road, near the top of Regent-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18251027-49-crimeloc273" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18251027-49-off271 t18251027-49-crimeloc273"></join> - there was a crowd looking at a horse which had fallen: I felt a pull at my pocket and turned round - a constable, who had the prisoner in his hand, asked if I had lost a handkerchief - I saw my handkerchief at the prisoner's feet.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18251027-49-person317">
                  ANGELIOUS 
                  BERTRAND
               <interp inst="t18251027-49-person317" type="surname" value="BERTRAND"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18251027-49-person317" type="given" value="ANGELIOUS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18251027-49-person317" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. On the 28th of September, about a quarter past two o'clock, I saw the prisoner and another boy coming down the street, and knowing the prisoner I followed them; there was a crowd through which Mr. Tonkin was going - the prisoner put his hand into his pocket and took the handkerchief out - I collared him, and told the gentleman what I had seen - the handkerchief was then on the ground.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18251027-49-verdict274" type="verdictDescription">
